text.tspan: Given a puzzle, without reducing symmetry we'll find a lot of redundant solutions. Rather than comparing solutions at the end and deleting the
ones which we detect as identical, we want to factor in symmetry into our solving algorithm so we don't spend the time searching for symmetric
solutions in the first place.
Consider a puzzle with a 2D square grid:
The goal shape has a lot of symmetry. A shape has symmetry if there is some transformation (in our case, rotations / mirroring) which can be
applied to get the same shape. Let's look at all of the possible orientations this piece could be in:
That's really only 2 possible orientations, with the others being redundant. We'll call these two groups orientation groups:
Let's look at the two piece of this puzzles and group their orientations like we did with the goal piece:
Piece 1 has 1 orientation group, the maximum amount of symmetry!
Piece 2 has 4 orientation groups.
Now let's start thinking about the solve algorithm. It works by fixing the goal piece in place and trying to fit each piece into it. While the goal
never changes orientation, we must consider any possible orientaiton for the pieces. Although it's not the focus of our discussion here, for each
orientation we also try any translation which can fit into the goal, without overlapping any existing placements in our search tree.
For example, trying to place the piece 2 in its original orientation:

If we've tried an orientation, we obviously don't need to try any of the other equivilent orientations in the same group. That reduces our problem
space a lot. Our first piece goes from 8 possible orientations to try down to one, and our second piece goes from 8 to 4. But this still leaves us with
multiple solutions that we want to consider as the same:
This happens because our goal has symmetries. That is, we can rotate the whole completed puzzle and still get the same overall shape, which is
considered by our algorithm so far to be a completely separate solution. Since we don't really want our algorithm to take the time searching for
duplicate solutions, it would be nice to eliminate them early on somehow.
You can imagine if we choose one piece and eliminated some of the remaining orientations from consideration, we won't have both of these
symmetric solutions anymore. Indeed, if we eliminating two of the orientation groups for the second piece:
Then we would only get a single solution, eliminating the redundant symmetric solution:
Why does this work, and how can we do it in a general case?
When we try one orientation for a piece, it's redundant to try the rotations of that piece in which the goal is symmetrical.
In this case, there's only one piece which it's advantageous to do this on. The first piece isn't a good candidate because it's already symmetrical
about the same rotations as the goal. That is, we already don't have to try any of its rotated forms because it's symmetrical itself.
In general we can't elimination orientations like this for more than one piece because we would need to start worrying about a piece's orientation
relative to other pieces, not just the goal piece. In more complex puzzles, we will look at every piece, consider which orientations we could
eliminate, then choose the piece which eliminates the the most.

So which symmetries can we eliminate? First, for each piece pick one from each group:
Piece 1 we can eliminate half, but piece 2 isn't symmetrical at all! We have to keep all of those orientations.
Next, for piece 1, which orientations can we eliminate based on goal symmetry? Actually, none! For each of the 4 orientations we have left,
the ones in the same orientation group for the goal piece are already eliminated. This is because it has all the same symmetries in
common with the goal so we already only have one to try from each orientation group.
So what about piece 2? Let's overlay the symmetry groups of the goal to see which can be eliminated:
We'll obviously pick piece 2 to eliminate orientations from, since we can eliminate 4 there instead of piece 1's zero.
A good rule of thumb is that more symmetry in the goal is better, and the less symmetry in a piece, the better a candidate it is.

Good! Without taking goal symmetry into account, we would have had to search for twice as long, and find a second redundant solution.
One thing to note about this symmetry reduction algorithm is that it makes very few assumptions about the underlying grid. As long as the grid
can tell you all possible orientations of a piece, you can reduce symmetries in the same way. For a 3-dimensional cubic grid, instead of 8
possible orientations there would be 24.
